<a id="Vector2i"></a>

# Vector2i

A 2D vector using integer coordinates.

<!-- classref-introduction-group -->

## Description

A 2-element structure that can be used to represent 2D grid coordinates or any other pair of integers.

It uses integer coordinates and is therefore preferable to [Vector2](Vector2.md) when exact precision is required. Note that the values are limited to 32 bits, and unlike [Vector2](Vector2.md) this cannot be configured with an engine build option. Use [int](int.md) or [PackedInt64Array](PackedInt64Array.md) if 64-bit values are needed.

\ **Note:** In a boolean context, a Vector2i will evaluate to ``false`` if it's equal to ``Vector2i(0, 0)``. Otherwise, a Vector2i will always evaluate to ``true``.

Down unit vector. Y is down in 2D, so this vector points +Y.

For a different behavior consider passing the result of [Vector2.ceil()](Vector2.md#Vector2_method_ceil), [Vector2.floor()](Vector2.md#Vector2_method_floor) or [Vector2.round()](Vector2.md#Vector2_method_round) to this constructor instead.

[Vector2i](Vector2i.md) **sign**\ (\ ) <span class="const">const</span> [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_method_sign)

## Operator Descriptions

<a id="Vector2i_operator_neq_Vector2i"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[bool](bool.md) **operator !=**\ (\ right\: [Vector2i](Vector2i.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_neq_Vector2i)

Returns ``true`` if the vectors are not equal.

<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_mod_Vector2i"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[Vector2i](Vector2i.md) **operator %**\ (\ right\: [Vector2i](Vector2i.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_mod_Vector2i)

Gets the remainder of each component of the **Vector2i** with the components of the given **Vector2i**. This operation uses truncated division, which is often not desired as it does not work well with negative numbers. Consider using [@GlobalScope.posmod()](@GlobalScope.md#@GlobalScope_method_posmod) instead if you want to handle negative numbers.

```
    print(Vector2i(10, -20) % Vector2i(7, 8)) # Prints (3, -4)
```


<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_mod_int"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[Vector2i](Vector2i.md) **operator %**\ (\ right\: [int](int.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_mod_int)

Gets the remainder of each component of the **Vector2i** with the given [int](int.md). This operation uses truncated division, which is often not desired as it does not work well with negative numbers. Consider using [@GlobalScope.posmod()](@GlobalScope.md#@GlobalScope_method_posmod) instead if you want to handle negative numbers.

```
    print(Vector2i(10, -20) % 7) # Prints (3, -6)
```


<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_mul_Vector2i"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[Vector2i](Vector2i.md) **operator ***\ (\ right\: [Vector2i](Vector2i.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_mul_Vector2i)

Multiplies each component of the **Vector2i** by the components of the given **Vector2i**.

```
    print(Vector2i(10, 20) * Vector2i(3, 4)) # Prints (30, 80)
```


<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_mul_float"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[Vector2](Vector2.md) **operator ***\ (\ right\: [float](float.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_mul_float)

Multiplies each component of the **Vector2i** by the given [float](float.md). Returns a [Vector2](Vector2.md).

```
    print(Vector2i(10, 15) * 0.9) # Prints (9.0, 13.5)
```


<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_mul_int"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[Vector2i](Vector2i.md) **operator ***\ (\ right\: [int](int.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_mul_int)

Multiplies each component of the **Vector2i** by the given [int](int.md).

<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_sum_Vector2i"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[Vector2i](Vector2i.md) **operator +**\ (\ right\: [Vector2i](Vector2i.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_sum_Vector2i)

Adds each component of the **Vector2i** by the components of the given **Vector2i**.

```
    print(Vector2i(10, 20) + Vector2i(3, 4)) # Prints (13, 24)
```


<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_dif_Vector2i"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[Vector2i](Vector2i.md) **operator -**\ (\ right\: [Vector2i](Vector2i.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_dif_Vector2i)

Subtracts each component of the **Vector2i** by the components of the given **Vector2i**.

```
    print(Vector2i(10, 20) - Vector2i(3, 4)) # Prints (7, 16)
```


<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_div_Vector2i"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[Vector2i](Vector2i.md) **operator /**\ (\ right\: [Vector2i](Vector2i.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_div_Vector2i)

Divides each component of the **Vector2i** by the components of the given **Vector2i**.

```
    print(Vector2i(10, 20) / Vector2i(2, 5)) # Prints (5, 4)
```


<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_div_float"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[Vector2](Vector2.md) **operator /**\ (\ right\: [float](float.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_div_float)

Divides each component of the **Vector2i** by the given [float](float.md). Returns a [Vector2](Vector2.md).

```
    print(Vector2i(1, 2) / 2.5) # Prints (0.4, 0.8)
```

<a id="Vector2i_operator_lt_Vector2i"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[bool](bool.md) **operator &lt;**\ (\ right\: [Vector2i](Vector2i.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_lt_Vector2i)

Compares two **Vector2i** vectors by first checking if the X value of the left vector is less than the X value of the `right` vector. If the X values are exactly equal, then it repeats this check with the Y values of the two vectors. This operator is useful for sorting vectors.

<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_lte_Vector2i"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[bool](bool.md) **operator &lt;=**\ (\ right\: [Vector2i](Vector2i.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_lte_Vector2i)

Compares two **Vector2i** vectors by first checking if the X value of the left vector is less than or equal to the X value of the `right` vector. If the X values are exactly equal, then it repeats this check with the Y values of the two vectors. This operator is useful for sorting vectors.

<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_eq_Vector2i"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[bool](bool.md) **operator ==**\ (\ right\: [Vector2i](Vector2i.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_eq_Vector2i)

Returns ``true`` if the vectors are equal.

<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_gt_Vector2i"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[bool](bool.md) **operator &gt;**\ (\ right\: [Vector2i](Vector2i.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_gt_Vector2i)

Compares two **Vector2i** vectors by first checking if the X value of the left vector is greater than the X value of the `right` vector. If the X values are exactly equal, then it repeats this check with the Y values of the two vectors. This operator is useful for sorting vectors.

<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_gte_Vector2i"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[bool](bool.md) **operator &gt;=**\ (\ right\: [Vector2i](Vector2i.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_gte_Vector2i)

Compares two **Vector2i** vectors by first checking if the X value of the left vector is greater than or equal to the X value of the `right` vector. If the X values are exactly equal, then it repeats this check with the Y values of the two vectors. This operator is useful for sorting vectors.

<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_idx_int"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[int](int.md) **operator []**\ (\ index\: [int](int.md)\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_idx_int)

Access vector components using their `index`. ``v[0]`` is equivalent to ``v.x``, and ``v[1]`` is equivalent to ``v.y``.

<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_unplus"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[Vector2i](Vector2i.md) **operator unary+**\ (\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_unplus)

Returns the same value as if the ``+`` was not there. Unary ``+`` does nothing, but sometimes it can make your code more readable.

<hr class="classref-item-separator"/>

<a id="Vector2i_operator_unminus"></a>

<!-- classref-operator -->

[Vector2i](Vector2i.md) **operator unary-**\ (\ ) [ðŸ”—](#Vector2i_operator_unminus)

Returns the negative value of the **Vector2i**. This is the same as writing ``Vector2i(-v.x, -v.y)``. This operation flips the direction of the vector while keeping the same magnitude.
